I’d been doing this for several blocks, long enough that the whole exercise had turned from time-passing to tiresome, but I kept doing because it seemed like bad luck to stop. I was drunk, obviously, although not very, just relatively — just a relatively drunk 28-year-old man who was in relatively good shape, feeling relatively happy. lead_paragraph: Growing up, I feared that my parents preferred my brother Brian. He was 17 months younger, a tree climber and mud-flinger who aced the “Disease Game” my father played with my other male siblings.

headline.main: The Disease Game

abstract: When two self-described tech geeks slide into a relationship that seems too easy, they design a monthlong trial to expose its flaws.
snippet: When two self-described tech geeks slide into a relationship that seems too easy, they design a monthlong trial to expose its flaws.
lead_paragraph: Several years ago, on a beautiful Valentine’s Day evening in San Francisco, a friend of mine and I decided to visit the California Academy of Sciences. The museum was love-themed for the occasion, with lectures about dating and exhibits of ancient dildos, contraptions that resembled medieval torture devices.

headline.main: Putting Love to the Stress Test
